I have a similar requirement.  I managed to get a quick and dirty solution working for my needs, but a more generic solution would be very helpful.

I have written a custom handler for encoding dates.  (In my scenario, date is serialized into an epoch and embedded in a dictionary, with $date as the key.  This is to conform to MongoDB's JSON format for dates.)  The encoding works perfectly.

```python
class DatetimeHandler(jsonpickle.handlers.BaseHandler):
    def flatten(self, obj, data):
        x = {"$date": int((obj - datetime.datetime(1970,1,1)).total_seconds())*1000}
        return x

jsonpickle.handlers.register(datetime.date, DatetimeHandler)
jsonpickle.handlers.register(datetime.time, DatetimeHandler)
jsonpickle.handlers.register(datetime.datetime, DatetimeHandler)
```

The problem I have is with decoding.  I have solved this with a relatively dirty hack, which is modifying jsonpickle's unpickler.py (and tags.py) to recognize $date as a tag and perform a custom restore:

```python
DOLLARDATE = '$date'

def _restore(self, obj):
        if has_tag(obj, tags.DOLLARDATE):
            restore = self._restore_dollardate

def _restore_dollardate(self, obj):
        return datetime.datetime(1970, 1, 1) + datetime.timedelta(milliseconds=obj[tags.DOLLARDATE])
```

This could be optimized to include an additional py/date tag or something similar, as aldanor mentions, but I think it would still require modifying unpickler.py.

