@jart @wchargin @dandelionmane

How would you create a `B` instance in C++?  For example, if you have some factory function, you could use something like: `.def(py::init([]() { return B::factory(); }))`.  As it is, it looks non-creatable.

Alternatively, if the class is polymorphic, one way you could do this is to define a [trampoline class](http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/advanced/classes.html#extended-trampoline-class-functionality) that wraps `B`, exposes its constructor, and tells pybind to always create a `MyB` instance when a `B` is constructed from Python:

```C++
class A {};
class B : public A {
protected B() : A() {}
};

// Later, in pybind binding code:
class MyB : public B {
public:
    MyB() : B() {}
};
py::class_<B, MyB>(m, "B")
    .def(py::init_alias<B>());
```

FYI the C style cast does work.  It might be nice to include that in the docs.  We use a spec file system (like sip) to generate the bindings so I've resorted to having the code generator use C style casts for every function/method.   I had to look up the correct format for a method cast so here it is in case anyone else cares:

n.def( "func", (CAST)( &func ), ... )

where CAST for C functions, namespace functions, or static functions is:
RTN_TYPE (*)(CALL_ARGS)

where CAST For methods is:
RTN_TYPE (CLASS::*)(CALL_ARGS)

```
struct Foo {
   static void sfunc( int a, const Foo& f );
   Foo method( const string& s );
};

m.def_static( "sfunc", (void (*)(int, const Foo&))( &Foo::sfunc ) );
m.def( "method", (Foo (Foo::*)(const string&))( &Foo::method ) );
```

